Modified-Alt-Text: Schematic showing electron scattering from proton revealing three point-like quarks inside. Similar to Rutherford's alpha scattering discovering nucleus. High-energy electrons have small wavelength to resolve quark-scale details. Scattering pattern confirms quark model of proton structure.

The graph shows how the critical magnetic fields of a type-II superconductor change with temperature, plotted against the normalized temperature T/Tc. The lower critical field Bc‚ÇÅ represents the magnetic field strength at which magnetic flux first begins to enter the material, marking the transition from perfect diamagnetism to the mixed (vortex) state. The upper critical field Bc‚ÇÇ represents the maximum field at which superconductivity can exist; above this value, the material becomes normal. As the temperature approaches the critical temperature Tc, superconductivity weakens, causing both critical fields to decrease, especially Bc‚ÇÇ, which drops rapidly. This behavior reflects the reduced ability of the material to expel or sustain magnetic fields as thermal energy disrupts the superconducting state.

Two rays hitting different planes at the same angle. They arrive parallel and reflect parallel. The path difference is equal to 2 multiplied by D multiplied by sin(theta) where D is the distance between planes.

Comparison of transverse and longitudinal waves using sound and strings. A guitar string vibrates up and down, demonstrating a transverse wave where the string‚Äôs motion is perpendicular to the direction of wave travel. An amplifier and speaker produce sound waves that travel outward through the air as longitudinal waves, shown by compressions and rarefactions. A sheet of paper and a handheld tuning fork vibrate back and forth in the same direction as the sound propagation, illustrating that sound waves in air are longitudinal, while waves in solids and water can have both transverse and longitudinal components.

The scatter plot shows Macroscopicity versus year from 1980 to 2020. Macroscopicity measures how large, massive, or ‚Äúmacroscopic‚Äù a system can be while still exhibiting quantum behavior, so higher values indicate experiments that push quantum effects to larger scales rather than simply larger physical size. Over time, the increase in Macroscopicity, especially the higher values appearing after 2000, suggests scientific progress driven by improved experimental techniques, measurement precision, and data collection methods, rather than changes in scale alone. The highlighted outlier, shown as a red diamond, represents an exceptional experiment that significantly exceeds typical results for its time, making it important because it challenges existing limits and motivates further investigation into how macroscopic quantum effects can be achieved.

This is a two part diagram of the behaviour of excess negative charge in conductors and insulators. In part (a), a conducting sphere with excess negative charge is shown. The extra electrons repel one another and are free to move, so they spread out and redistribute themselves uniformly over the outer surface of the sphere. In part (b), an insulating sphere with excess negative charge is shown. Because electrons are not free to move within an insulator, the excess negative charge remains localized near where it was placed rather than spreading over the surface. The figure illustrates the key difference between conductors and insulators in how electric charge can move and redistribute.

Position vs time curve with several peaks and valleys labeled. Slope is positive where the curve rises and negative where it falls; slope is zero at local maxima and minima. Use steepness to compare instantaneous speeds at different points.

diffraction grating functions inside a spectroscope. Light from a source enters the instrument and travels toward a diffraction grating. As the light strikes the grating, it is diffracted and separated into different wavelengths, which propagate at different angles due to constructive and destructive interference. Mirrors redirect the diffracted light toward a detector. Each wavelength follows a distinct path, producing a spread of colors at the detector that forms a spectrum. The diagram illustrates how diffraction enables the analysis of light by wavelength, allowing a spectroscope to identify the composition of a light source. At the same time, it highlights that diffraction is an inherent wave effect that can also limit image sharpness by spreading light rather than keeping it perfectly focused.

Ray diagram illustrating image formation by a concave mirror and the variables used in mirror and lens calculations. The object is placed at a distance do from the mirror with height ho, while the image forms at distance di with height hi. Rays are drawn using standard construction rules: one ray travels parallel to the principal axis and reflects through the focal point F, another passes through the focal point and reflects parallel to the axis, and a third reflects symmetrically about the normal. These rays intersect to locate the image position and size. The focal length f characterizes the mirror‚Äôs curvature and determines how strongly it converges light. The relationships among do, di, and f are described by the mirror (lens) equation, which is used to predict image location and magnification in optical systems such as mirrors, lenses, telescopes, and cameras.

Graph showing potential energy vs separation distance for two nuclei. Coulomb repulsion creates barrier (hump) at intermediate distances. If nuclei have sufficient kinetic energy to overcome barrier, they fuse and drop into deep attractive well at small separations, releasing energy. Explains temperature requirement for fusion.

Line graph of water temperature over time. Temperature rises from near room temperature to about boiling, then levels off near the boiling temperature. Use the y-intercept to read the starting temperature and the slope to see how quickly temperature changes.

Qualitative velocity vs time graph labeled with points. Velocity increases and decreases over time; upward slopes indicate positive acceleration and downward slopes indicate negative acceleration. Steeper sections indicate larger acceleration magnitude.

Van de Graaff generator diagram showing: battery (A) supplies charge to pointed conductor, points spray charge onto moving insulating belt, pointed conductor (B) in large sphere picks charge off belt. Charge accumulates in sphere to very high voltage. Shows principle of electrostatic charge accumulation and acceleration.

Particle composition diagram. Top: proton (uud quarks) and neutron (udd quarks) - both baryons with three quarks. Bottom: positive pion (u and anti-d) and negative pion (d and anti-u) - both mesons with quark-antiquark pair. Arrows show quark spins. Colors add to white. Shows fundamental difference between baryons and mesons.

Key elements like the coil's orientation and current direction reveal potential trends in magnetic flux and illustrate the relationships governing electromagnetic theory.

Solar absorption spectrum showing continuous rainbow with black lines (Fraunhofer lines) at specific wavelengths. Hot solar interior emits continuous spectrum. Cooler exterior gas absorbs specific wavelengths, creating dark lines. Lines reveal chemical composition of Sun's atmosphere.
A circuit with 3 resistances connected as follows: R_1(75 ohms) is connected in series with R_S1(80 ohms) and R_S2(45.71 ohms). Both R_S1 and R_S2 are connected in parallel to each other.

Projectile motion diagram on x‚Äìy axes. A kicked ball follows a curved red trajectory with several ball positions shown along the arc. A straight displacement vector d points from the launch point to the landing point at an angle Œ∏ above the horizontal. Dashed lines form a right triangle with horizontal leg labeled x and vertical leg labeled y.

Sound wave generation diagram. A vibrating string moves to the right, compressing the air in front of it to create a region of compression and expanding the air behind it to create a region of rarefaction. These alternating compressions and rarefactions propagate through the air as a longitudinal sound wave, illustrating how mechanical vibrations in a source produce sound.

Velocity vs. time graph titled ‚ÄúJet Car Velocity.‚Äù The green curve starts near 165 meters per second (m/s) at t = 0 seconds (s), rises quickly, then levels off near 250 m/s by about 50‚Äì70 s. The image consists of two graphs representing spectral irradiance over different wavelength ranges, with both displaying spectral parts labeled accordingly. The left graph illustrates the spectral irradiance in nanometers, highlighting a sharp peak around the visible spectrum (approximately 400‚Äì700 nm) while tapering off towards the ultraviolet (UV) and infrared (IR) ends. This peak occurs because the Sun emits most of its energy at visible wavelengths due to its surface temperature. The right graph features a broader spectral range, incorporating an expanded view from UV to near-infrared wavelengths, with color coding indicating different spectral regions such as UV, visible, and IR (including UVA and UVB). The dominant colors in the visible range create a vivid rainbow effect, emphasizing the intensity of solar irradiance at these wavelengths. Both graphs reveal a notable decrease in intensity beyond the visible spectrum, indicating a significant decline in spectral irradiance as it moves into the infrared and ultraviolet ranges, which has implications for understanding energy distribution and environmental impacts related to solar radiation.

This diagram shows a DC RC circuit with a switch, illustrating charging and discharging behavior in a first-order system. A 5.64 V voltage source (V5) is connected to the circuit through a single-pole switch (SW2), which controls whether the circuit is energized. When the switch is closed, current flows from the source to a node that feeds a resistor R7 (6.64 Œ©) and a capacitor C4 (1.64 ¬µF) connected in parallel to ground. The resistor provides an immediate conduction path, while the capacitor initially behaves like a short circuit and begins to store electric charge. Over time, the capacitor voltage rises toward the supply voltage as the charging current decreases exponentially, governed by the RC time constant œÑ = R7¬∑C4. When the switch is opened, the source is disconnected and the capacitor discharges through the resistor, releasing its stored energy as the voltage across C4 decays back toward zero. This circuit visually reinforces core concepts in transient analysis, including switch-controlled dynamics, energy storage in capacitors, and exponential voltage and current behavior in RC systems.

Two simplified graphs illustrate a disturbance in freeway traffic as a function of position. The top graph plots velocity versus position, showing traffic moving at a higher, constant speed, then smoothly slowing down through a transition region, and finally continuing at a lower constant speed. The bottom graph plots excess density versus position, showing a localized rectangular spike where vehicle density is higher than normal, surrounded by regions of zero excess density. Together, the graphs show how a localized increase in car density corresponds to a drop in traffic speed, representing a traffic jam or congestion wave propagating along the freeway.

the first law of thermodynamics for a system. Heat Q enters or leaves the system, and work W is done by or on the system. The change in internal energy is shown as ŒîU = Q ‚àí W, where (Q) represents the net heat transfer into the system and W represents the net work done by the system. Arrows indicate heat flowing into and out of the system (Q_in and Q_out) and work done by the system (W_out) or on the system (W_in), emphasizing energy conservation through heat and work transfers.

the first overtone resonance in a tube closed at one end, where air displacement is zero at the closed end and maximum at the open end; the standing wave fits three-quarters of a wavelength within the tube length, producing a higher-frequency resonance characteristic of closed-pipe acoustics.

This contour plot illustrates a three-dimensional surface represented in a two-dimensional format, showing the relationship between two variables, ùë•‚ÇÅ and ùë•‚ÇÇ. The axes are labeled ùë•‚ÇÅ (horizontal) and ùë•‚ÇÇ (vertical), each ranging from approximately ‚àí3 to 3. The plot features several contour lines in blue, green, and red, with numeric labels such as 100, 250, and 500 indicating constant function values. The contours form a convex pattern resembling a parabolic surface, suggesting a local minimum at the origin where the function value is lowest. Gradient vectors at any point would point perpendicular to the contour lines and toward this minimum, indicating the direction of steepest descent. This shows that as ùë•‚ÇÅ and ùë•‚ÇÇ approach zero, the function value decreases, a key idea in optimization that helps explain convergence toward stable solutions.

Circular formula wheel diagram divided into sections showing relationships between voltage, current, resistance, and power. Inner quarter circles contain variables that equal corresponding outer quarter circle equations, providing quick reference for Ohm's law and power calculations.

Illustration showing magnetic pole interactions. Top: two north poles (N-N) repel with arrows pushing apart. Middle: two south poles (S-S) repel. Bottom: opposite poles (N-S) attract with arrows pulling together. Demonstrates like poles repel, unlike poles attract.

Ice-to-water entropy increase diagram. On the left, ice is shown as an ordered structure with molecules arranged in a regular lattice. An arrow labeled (ŒîS > 0) points to the right, where liquid water is shown with molecules moving randomly in many directions. The diagram illustrates that when ice melts into water, molecular order decreases, disorder increases, and entropy increases due to heat transfer into the system.

A rotating coil with vertical wire segments moving through magnetic field. Velocity vector of wire makes angle Œ∏ with field direction. Component of velocity perpendicular to field determines induced emf magnitude.

Position vs time graph for a runner that rises then stays flat. The motion includes a forward move followed by a stop. Use the overall change in position divided by total time to compute average velocity.

a comparison of materials arranged by their ability to conduct electric charge. An arrow across the top indicates increasing electrical conductivity from left to right. Materials are grouped into three broad categories: insulators, semiconductors, and conductors. On the left, insulators such as dry air, dry wood, rubber, and glass have very low ability to conduct charge, meaning electric charges do not move easily through them. In the middle, semiconductors such as silicon, germanium, and seawater have intermediate conducting ability that lies between insulators and conductors. On the right, conductors such as carbon, mercury, iron, aluminum, copper, and silver allow electric charge to move readily. Slashes on the arrow indicate that there are very large gaps in conductivity between these categories, but the scale is compressed to fit on the page. Numbers listed beneath each material represent resistivity values in units of ohm‚Äìmeters, which measure how strongly a material resists the flow of electric charge. Lower resistivity corresponds to better electrical conduction.

The diagram illustrates the principles of electromagnetic force acting on a current-carrying conductor within a magnetic field. Key elements include a resistor labeled 'R,' a current 'I' flowing through the conductor indicated by an arrow, and a magnetic field 'B' represented with circles and crosses indicating field direction. Axes are marked along the horizontal (x) and vertical (y) dimensions, with relevant symbols showing the flow of current and the resulting magnetic force 'F_m' acting on the conductor. The interrelationship between current and magnetic fields is emphasized, highlighting the dynamics of forces involved when a conductor moves with velocity 'u' in the magnetic field. This representation elucidates the foundational concept of electromagnetism, demonstrating how electric currents interact with magnetic fields to produce motion.

Feynman diagram with time vertical axis, distance horizontal axis. Two positively charged particles (vertical lines) exchange virtual photon (wavy line connecting them). Particles repel due to photon exchange. Diagram read bottom to top shows particle trajectories diverging after exchange. Demonstrates quantum mechanical electromagnetic repulsion.

The horizontal ground on which the weightlifter stands is labeled ‚Äúy = 0.‚Äù The motion of the barbell lift at three positions is shown. In the final position, the barbell is directly above the lifter‚Äôs head with arms fully extended vertically. At this final position, the barbell is momentarily at rest, meaning it is not moving. In this position, two arrows point from the center of the barbell: the vector F‚Ççweightlifter‚Çé points vertically upward along the vertical axis, and the vector w = F‚Ççgravity‚Çé points vertically downward along the same axis. Because the barbell is not accelerating at this point, Newton‚Äôs First Law applies and the forces are balanced. The vertical distance between the ground and the bottom of the barbell is h, and the work done by the lifter in raising the barbell is stored as gravitational potential energy at this final height.

Resultant vector on x‚Äìy axes with a labeled magnitude and an angle above the +x direction. Images of a ruler and a protractor indicate measuring vector length for magnitude and measuring the angle from the reference axis for direction.

Line graph titled ‚ÄúDensity vs Temperature at Different Pressure.‚Äù The horizontal axis represents temperature, while the vertical axis represents density. Two sets of experimental data are shown for pressures P = 2.5 and P = 2.7, each plotted with data points and small error bars, along with corresponding smooth curves representing ideal gas law predictions at those pressures. For both pressures, density decreases as temperature increases, illustrating the inverse relationship between temperature and density for a gas when pressure is held approximately constant. At every temperature, the curve for P = 2.7 lies above the curve for P = 2.5, indicating that higher pressure results in a higher density at the same temperature, consistent with thermodynamic expectations. The ideal gas law prediction curves follow the same downward trend and remain close to the measured data, showing good agreement between theory and experiment. Small deviations between the measured points and the ideal curves suggest minor non-ideal effects or experimental uncertainty, but the overall behavior strongly supports the ideal gas model. The graph visually reinforces the physical principle that increasing temperature causes gas particles to spread out, reducing density, while increasing pressure compresses the gas and increases density.
Schematic for a variable volatge source that is powering a bulb with 6.8 Volts (V).
Velocity vs time graph shown as a straight line rising from left to right. A constant slope indicates constant acceleration. Use the slope Œîv/Œît to compute acceleration.

Diagram illustrating angular velocity geometry for a rotating rigid body. An irregular teal shape represents the body. A fixed origin O is shown at lower left, with a position vector R pointing to a reference point O‚Ä≤ inside the body. From O‚Ä≤, a relative position vector r·µ¢ points to a particle P on the body, marked in red. The absolute position vector R·µ¢ runs from O directly to P. The vectors emphasize the decomposition of a particle‚Äôs position into a reference point plus a relative displacement, as used when describing angular velocity and rotational motion.

This diagram illustrates vector addition of two forces using a head-to-tail construction and their resulting force. The black vectors F‚ÇÅ and F‚ÇÇ are drawn sequentially: F‚ÇÅ acts at an angle Œ∏‚ÇÇ above the horizontal baseline, and F‚ÇÇ begins at the head of F‚ÇÅ, rising steeply with its own orientation defined by angle Œ∏‚ÇÉ. The grey diagonal vector F·µ£ represents the resultant force, drawn from the tail of F‚ÇÅ directly to the head of F‚ÇÇ, showing the net effect of the two forces acting together. Several angles are labeled to clarify the geometry: œÜ measures the inclination of the resultant relative to the horizontal, Œ∏‚ÇÅ shows the angle between F·µ£ and F‚ÇÅ, and Œ∏‚ÇÇ and Œ∏‚ÇÉ describe the orientations of F‚ÇÅ and F‚ÇÇ, respectively. Educationally, the figure emphasizes that vector addition depends on both magnitude and direction, not just size, and that the resultant force can be found geometrically or analytically using trigonometry or component methods. This construction is commonly used in statics and dynamics to analyze systems where multiple forces act simultaneously on an object.

The illustration presents varieties of crystal lattice structures: cubic body-centered (bcc), cubic face-centered (fcc), and hexagonal. Each structure shows a distinct arrangement of atoms, represented by spheres, with connecting lines indicating bonds within the lattice. The bcc structure includes atoms at the cube corners and one atom at the center. This configuration, common in elements such as iron (Fe), vanadium (V), niobium (Nb), and chromium (Cr), supports efficient packing and strong metallic bonding, contributing to structural strength. The fcc structure places atoms at the cube corners and at the center of each face. This closely packed arrangement is found in metals such as aluminum (Al), nickel (Ni), silver (Ag), copper (Cu), and gold (Au). Its dense packing allows atoms to slide past one another more easily, which explains its high ductility and good electrical conductivity. The hexagonal lattice uses a hexagon-shaped repeating pattern with atoms arranged to maximize packing. This hexagonal close-packed (hcp) structure appears in materials like titanium (Ti), zinc (Zn), magnesium (Mg), and cadmium (Cd). It has a coordination number of twelve, meaning each atom touches twelve neighboring atoms, leading to strong atomic bonding and high strength, but less ability to deform compared to fcc structures.

Timeline of universe from Big Bang to present. Horizontal axis: time from 10‚Åª‚Å¥¬≥ seconds to 10‚Åπ years. Vertical axis: energy from 10¬π‚Åπ GeV to 1 GeV. Color gradients show eras: Planck epoch, GUT era, Quark era, Hadron era, Lepton era, Nucleosynthesis, Atomic era, Galaxy formation. Graph showing three blackbody radiation curves at different temperatures (3000K, 4000K, 5000K). Horizontal axis shows wavelength, vertical axis shows intensity. Higher temperature curves shift left toward shorter wavelengths (UV) and have higher peak intensity. Shape cannot be explained by classical physics - led to quantum theory.

Vector addition on x‚Äìy axes with compass directions shown at left. a car headlight or spotlight uses a parabolic mirror to control light direction. The bulb is placed at the focal point of the parabolic mirror, so light rays emitted in all directions reflect off the mirror and emerge as parallel rays. This produces a bright, focused beam that travels long distances without spreading out significantly. The same physical principle is used in solar collectors, where sunlight is reflected and concentrated at a focal point to produce heat for energy generation, demonstrating how mirror geometry controls light propagation and energy concentration.

The representation showcases a scatter plot with a smooth curve fitted through the data points. The x-axis is labeled ‚ÄúTransverse displacement (nm)‚Äù, ranging from 0 to 1,000 nanometers, and the y-axis is marked ‚ÄúNorm counts,‚Äù extending up to 1.5. Blue dots indicate individual measured data points, while the black line shows a clear sinusoidal trend. This oscillating pattern arises from diffraction effects, where waves interfere constructively at some transverse positions and destructively at others. As the displacement changes, the relative phase of the waves shifts, producing alternating maxima and minima in the counts. The spacing of the peaks and valleys reveals information about the spacing or arrangement of features in the material causing the diffraction, making the pattern useful for probing underlying structure rather than just visualizing the data distribution.

Photograph of LIGO control room in Hanford, Washington. Computer monitors and equipment for detecting gravitational waves. Scientists search for graviton through LIGO and particle accelerator experiments like LHC. Evidence may be indirect - like footprints in sand rather than seeing graviton directly.

Simple circuit diagram with a battery and connecting wire. Arrows show conventional current direction from positive to negative terminal (opposite to electron flow), illustrating basic current flow in a closed circuit.

Diagram of a block on an inclined plane showing the primary forces acting on it. A rectangular block rests on a sloped surface. The downward blue arrow labeled ùëä represents the block‚Äôs weight acting vertically due to gravity. A green arrow labeled ùëÅ points upward and perpendicular to the inclined surface, representing the normal force exerted by the plane on the block. A brown arrow labeled ùêπ acts along the surface of the incline, representing the frictional force opposing the block‚Äôs tendency to slide down the slope. This diagram illustrates how forces on an incline are not aligned with the horizontal and vertical axes, and highlights the role of the normal force and friction in balancing gravity. It provides a clear visual basis for analyzing equilibrium and motion on inclined planes using Newton‚Äôs laws.

Graph titled ‚ÄúVoltage vs Current of Four Different Circuits‚Äù showing the relationship between voltage (vertical axis, in volts) and current (horizontal axis, in milliamps) for four separate electrical circuits. Each circuit‚Äôs data points form a straight line, indicating a linear voltage‚Äìcurrent relationship consistent with Ohm‚Äôs law. Dotted trendlines are drawn through each set of points, with equations labeled above them; the slope of each line represents the effective resistance of that circuit. Circuit 2 has the steepest slope, meaning it has the highest resistance (a small increase in current requires a large increase in voltage), while Circuit 4 has the shallowest slope, indicating the lowest resistance. Circuits 1 and 3 fall between these extremes. The small intercept values near zero show minimal offset or measurement error. Overall, the graph illustrates how different circuit resistances affect the voltage required to drive a given current, reinforcing the idea that resistance determines the proportionality between voltage and current in linear, resistive systems.

On the left side, magnetic dipoles in a small volume are shown with scattered directions when no external magnetic field is applied, meaning B = 0. In this case, thermal motion causes the dipoles to remain randomly oriented. On the right side, when an external magnetic field B is applied, the magnetic dipoles are oriented in the same direction as the field. Each dipole experiences a torque due to the magnetic field, which causes it to rotate and gradually align with the field over time.

An astronaut uses an electronic timer to measure the time for a light pulse to travel from a source to a mirror and back inside her spacecraft. In the astronaut‚Äôs frame, the light moves straight up and down over a fixed distance. An observer on Earth sees the spacecraft moving, so the light follows a longer diagonal path and takes more time. This illustrates time dilation, where the observed time Œît is greater than the proper time Œît‚ÇÄ by the relativistic factor Œ≥ = 1/‚àö(1 ‚àí v¬≤/c¬≤).

Natural convection heating system inside a house. A gravity furnace heats air near the floor, causing the warm air to rise and circulate along the ceiling. As the air cools near the walls and windows, it becomes denser and sinks back down toward the floor. Blue arrows indicate cooler, sinking air, and red arrows indicate warmer, rising air. This continuous circulation shows convection driven by temperature differences and density changes in air.
Simple circuit with a switch and a resistor.

This diagram illustrates the kinetic theory of gases, showing gas particles as small spheres moving randomly within a container, each leaving a faint trail that represents its recent motion. The particles travel in straight lines between collisions, changing direction only when they collide with other particles or the container walls. The variation in trail length and direction indicates that particles have a range of speeds and move isotropically, reflecting the microscopic origin of temperature as a measure of average kinetic energy. Educationally, the diagram emphasizes that gas pressure arises from countless elastic collisions with the container walls, while macroscopic properties like pressure, temperature, and volume emerge statistically from this chaotic microscopic motion. It also highlights key assumptions of the kinetic model: particles are far apart, intermolecular forces are negligible except during collisions, and total kinetic energy increases as temperature rises.

A detailed schematic representation of an Extreme Ultraviolet (EUV) Lithography Exposure System, illustrating its components and functionality. The diagram is segmented into various parts, clearly labeled to indicate their roles. It features a reflective mask, EUV source collector, and illuminator optics, all aligned to focus EUV radiation onto a silicon wafer, specifically stated to be 300 mm in diameter. The system operates using 13.5 nm radiation, which is crucial for achieving high-resolution patterns necessary for advanced semiconductor manufacturing. Key annotations highlight that the optics are entirely reflective and that the entire optical pathway functions within a vacuum environment to prevent interference and ensure accuracy. The organization of this exposure system emphasizes the integration of precise optics in lithography.

The image features two diagrams illustrating the concept of the cross product of two vectors, A and B. On the left, a hand gesture symbolizes the right-hand rule for determining the direction of the resultant vector, A √ó B, with the thumb pointing in the direction of the resultant and the fingers curling from vector A to vector B. The angle Œ∏ is marked, showing the orientation between the two vectors. On the right, a conical surface represents the magnitude of the cross product as the area of the parallelogram formed by A and B. The size of this area depends on the angle between the vectors: it increases as the angle opens and reaches its maximum when the vectors are perpendicular at 90 degrees. This ties the angle between the vectors directly to the magnitude of the cross product, alongside the use of the right-hand rule to determine direction.

Comparison of two historical models of the atom. On the left is Thomson‚Äôs plum-pudding model, in which negatively charged electrons are embedded within a diffuse, uniform sphere of positive charge. In this model, the positive charge fills the entire atom, and the electrons are distributed throughout it like plums in a pudding. On the right is Rutherford‚Äôs nuclear model of the atom. In this model, a small, dense, positively charged nucleus is located at the center of the atom, while electrons move around the nucleus in extended orbits. The diagram emphasizes that the nucleus is extremely small compared with the size of the electron orbits; its size is greatly exaggerated for visibility. Together, the two drawings illustrate the major shift in understanding atomic structure from a diffuse positive charge to a concentrated central nucleus.

Photograph of industrial steam turbine generator. High-pressure steam from coal burning strikes turbine blades, rotating shaft connected to electrical generator. Large industrial-scale power generation equipment for producing electricity.

binoculars use prisms and total internal reflection to redirect light toward the observer‚Äôs eyes. Light rays entering the binoculars travel into glass prisms, where they strike internal surfaces at angles greater than the critical angle. Instead of refracting out of the prism, the light undergoes total internal reflection, allowing it to be reflected efficiently without the energy loss that occurs with metallic mirrors. The prisms are arranged as corner reflectors, which reverse and reorient the image so it appears upright and correctly oriented to the viewer. This optical path also allows binoculars to be compact while maintaining a long effective light path for magnification. The same physical principle is used in fiber-optic cables, where light is guided through glass or plastic fibers by repeated total internal reflection, enabling high-speed transmission of data for internet, telephone, and cable television systems.

The diagram displays a representation of a helical structure, characterized by a series of spiraling lines that denote magnetic field lines, illustrated in black, along a central axis depicted in green. The helical lines are numbered sequentially from 1 to N, suggesting multiple loops or windings around the axis. Magnetic field lines pass through the surface enclosed by each loop, and each loop adds to the total magnetic effect. Key equations are presented in green text, where ùúì = B ¬∑ S shows that the magnetic flux through one loop depends on how strong the magnetic field is and the area of the loop, while ùúÜ = Nùúì indicates that the total flux linkage increases as more loops are added. Together, these relationships show that the total magnetic linkage builds up from the contributions of all loops and depends on both the field strength and the number of loops.
Position vs time graph with points forming a curve that becomes steeper. Increasing steepness indicates increasing velocity. Use the slope at a chosen time to estimate instantaneous velocity.

Electric field diagram showing two opposite point charges, with a red dot on the left representing a positive charge and a blue dot on the right representing a negative charge. Gray field lines originate at the positive charge and curve through space to terminate at the negative charge, with arrows indicating the direction a positive test charge would move. The lines are more densely packed near the charges, indicating stronger electric fields in those regions, and spread out farther away where the field is weaker. This visualization emphasizes that electric forces are mediated by an electric field filling the surrounding space, not by direct contact between charges, and illustrates how the field‚Äôs direction and strength determine the motion and interaction of charged particles.

Two circular current-carrying loops, labeled 1 and 2, are placed close to each other and may be parallel or angled relative to one another. Each loop carries a current, with the direction of current flow shown along the circular paths. The current in loop 1 generates a magnetic field that spreads through space and passes through loop 2, linking the two loops magnetically. This interaction is the basis of mutual inductance, where a changing current in one loop can induce an effect in the other. A vector R‚ÇÇ‚ÇÅ connects a small current element on loop 1 to a point on loop 2, pointing from the source of the magnetic field to where its influence is felt. Together, the loops and vector illustrate how magnetic fields produced by one circuit affect another nearby circuit, forming the physical foundation for inductive coupling.
Text explaining that beyond peak frequency in blackbody spectrum, photons at particular frequencies become less probable, causing intensity decrease at high frequencies.

The chart illustrates the evolution of semiconductor manufacturing processes from 1970 to 2020, focusing on key metrics such as node sizes and wafer dimensions. The y-axis represents feature sizes in microns, ranging from 0.01 to 10 microns, while the x-axis denotes the timeline from 1970 to 2020. Various colors differentiate elements: pink for node sizes, blue for wafer sizes, and green for de-magnification ratios, indicating the scaling of technology over decades. A notable downward trend visible on the chart showcases a consistent reduction in node size from 6.1 microns in 1970 to 13.5 nanometers (or 0.0135 microns) by 2020, reflecting significant advancements in fabrication technologies. The de-magnification ratios are also highlighted, showing a transition from 1:1 to 4:1, emphasizing the increasing complexity and precision required in semiconductor manufacturing. This data underscores the rapid technological progress and miniaturization within the industry, ultimately impacting performance, power efficiency, and scalability of electronic devices.

The image represents a three-dimensional coordinate system illustrating spherical coordinates, characterized by the radius ùëü, polar angle ùúÉ, and azimuthal angle ùúô. This coordinate system is commonly used to describe the magnetic field produced by a magnetic dipole, such as a bar magnet or a tiny current loop. In this context, the coordinates help specify the direction and strength of the magnetic field at different points around the dipole. The axes are labeled with the x-axis extending horizontally, the y-axis perpendicular to it, and the z-axis extending vertically, which is typically aligned with the dipole‚Äôs magnetic moment. The distance ùëü measures how far a point is from the center of the dipole, ùúÉ is the vertical angle measured down from the z-axis, and ùúô is the horizontal angle measured around the z-axis. A circular shape, marked in blue, signifies the plane in which the angles are defined, while dashed lines show how a point projects onto the coordinate axes. This system emphasizes the relationship between the spherical coordinates and their Cartesian counterparts.

An S-shaped microstrip patch antenna is shown radiating electromagnetic waves. The shape of the patch controls how currents flow along the antenna, causing charges to oscillate back and forth along the S-shaped path. This oscillating current produces a time-varying electric field, which in turn generates a time-varying magnetic field. The electric field is perpendicular to the magnetic field, and both fields change together as the wave propagates. The direction of wave propagation is perpendicular to both fields, forming a transverse electromagnetic wave. The S-shape alters the current path length and distribution, which affects the radiation pattern, resonance, and directionality of the emitted waves. This illustrates how antenna geometry directly influences electromagnetic radiation behavior.

Graph of exposure wavelength versus resolution range. Line is drawn from the G line to the immersion points, and then down to the EUV and DP (double patterning) line. The x-axis, marked as the resolution range (measured in nanometers), spans from 10,000 nm down to 1 nm, while the y-axis, denoting exposure wavelength (also measured in nanometers), ranges from 8 nm up to 800 nm. Over time, the industry has progressively shifted from the G Line at approximately 436 nm, through i-Line at 365 nm, to various forms of deep ultraviolet (DUV) lithography. Immersive and dry techniques utilizing KrF (248 nm) and ArF (193 nm) wavelengths have pushed the boundaries of minimum feature size downwards. As these methods approached their limits, immersion lithography emerged around these wavelengths, further enhancing resolution by changing the medium between the lens and wafer to water, consequently increasing the effective numerical aperture. A compelling deviation occurs when the graph dives steeply towards the left as it transitions from ArF immersion to extreme ultraviolet (EUV) lithography, which employs a significantly lower wavelength of 13.5 nm. However, moving into the EUV regime demanded overcoming extensive technical hurdles related to light source power, optical system precision, photoresist sensitivity, and mask defectivity. Numerical aperture indicates how tightly the optics can focus light.

Longitudinal wave on a toy spring. A person pushes and pulls the spring horizontally, creating regions of compression and rarefaction that move to the right. The graph illustrates trends in functional CPU scaling over time, spanning from 2008 to 2030, with a logarithmic vertical axis labeled ‚ÄúLog (Functional CPU Scaling)‚Äù and a horizontal axis denoting ‚ÄúYear of 1st Production.‚Äù The curves show different strategies used to improve CPU performance as traditional transistor scaling slows. Design Technology Co-Optimization (DTCO) refers to improving performance by optimizing circuit design, layout, and architecture within a given technology node, while System Technology Co-Optimization (STCO) goes further by co-developing the chip together with packaging, memory, and system-level technologies. Key milestones such as 14 nm and 7 nm mark points where shrinking transistor sizes alone provided diminishing returns due to physical and economic limits. The green line highlights a shift away from relying only on smaller transistors toward design-based and system-level solutions, showing how DTCO helps recover performance gains even when scaling slows. This trend explains why performance continues to improve despite the limits of traditional Moore‚Äôs-law scaling: innovation increasingly comes from smarter design choices and system integration rather than transistor size reduction alone.

PET scanner diagram showing circular detector ring around patient. Positron from radiotracer annihilates with electron, producing two 0.511 MeV gamma rays traveling in opposite directions. Detectors record coincident gamma ray pairs, determining emission line location. Computer analyzes multiple events to form precise 3D image.

Comparison of gravitational potential energy and electric potential energy using similar visual models. On the left, a ball is shown at two different heights above Earth. An upward arrow indicates that gravitational potential energy increases as the ball is raised higher in Earth‚Äôs gravitational field, which points downward toward Earth. On the right, a positive charge is shown at two different distances from a negative charge. An upward arrow indicates that electric potential energy increases as the positive charge moves farther away from the negative charge, opposite the direction of the electric field. The diagram emphasizes the analogy between gravitational and electric potential energy: in both cases, potential energy depends on position within a field.

Position vs time graph with a curve that becomes steeper over time. The increasing slope indicates the object‚Äôs velocity is increasing (accelerating).

Relativistic momentum versus speed graph showing p_rel on the vertical axis and speed u as a fraction of the speed of light (c) on the horizontal axis. Momentum increases slowly at low speeds, closely matching classical momentum, then rises sharply as u approaches (c). A dashed vertical line at u = c indicates that the speed of light cannot be reached. The graph illustrates that relativistic momentum increases without bound as velocity approaches the speed of light, ensuring momentum conservation in all inertial reference frames and preventing massive objects from reaching or exceeding c.

a Schmidt‚ÄìCassegrain telescope illustrating how incoming parallel light from a distant object enters the telescope, reflects off the large concave primary mirror, then reflects from a smaller convex secondary mirror before being brought to focus at the focal plane near the observer‚Äôs eye. This folded optical path allows the telescope to have a long effective focal length while remaining physically compact. The design improves light-gathering power and image clarity, making it widely used in astronomical observations to view faint and distant objects such as planets, stars, and galaxies.

The diagram illustrates a double-slit experimental setup used in wave and quantum mechanics emphasizing the interaction of incoming waves as they pass through two slits on a screen. Key elements include the vertical axis marked as z which indicates the position of a detector, and a horizontal segment labeled L representing the distance from the screen to the detector. The angle œÜ is depicted, suggesting the relationship between the path length variations due to the slits. The incoming waves are represented on the left side as a series of parallel lines, indicating wavefronts. This setup is essential for demonstrating interference patterns, revealing fundamental principles about wave-particle duality and the behavior of light and matter. The spatial relationship and indicated angles suggest that as the distance from the slits increases, the observed patterns will change.

Multi-step fission diagram. Step 1: neutron absorbed by large nucleus adds energy. Step 2: nucleus deforms like liquid drop, narrows in middle. Step 3: fewer nucleons in contact, Coulomb repulsion breaks nucleus into two parts plus several neutrons. Energy released. Step 4: Additional neutrons can trigger more fissions - chain reaction basis.

Two photographs comparing field patterns using iron filings. Part (a): filings around energized solenoid. Part (b): filings around bar magnet. Patterns nearly identical, especially at ends, demonstrating solenoid's equivalence to bar magnet.

Photograph of Large Hadron Collider tunnel at CERN on Swiss-French border. Shows massive cylindrical detector equipment and infrastructure in underground tunnel. LHC is particle accelerator designed to study fundamental particles through high-energy collisions. World's largest and most powerful particle collider.

Comparison of concave and convex mirrors and their focal lengths. In the concave mirror (left), parallel incoming light rays reflect and converge at a focal point F located in front of the mirror, giving the mirror a positive focal length f. This converging behavior allows concave mirrors to form real or virtual depending on the object‚Äôs position relative to the focal point. In the convex mirror (right), parallel rays reflect and diverge outward, appearing to originate from a focal point F located behind the mirror, which is indicated as a negative focal length. Convex mirrors always form virtual, upright, and reduced images because reflected rays never actually meet in front of the mirror.

Superposition of nonidentical waves diagram. Wave 1 and Wave 2 have different wavelengths and amplitudes and overlap in the same region of space. When combined, the resulting wave shows a complex pattern with some regions of increased amplitude (constructive interference) and other regions of reduced amplitude (destructive interference). The diagram illustrates that most real wave interactions produce mixed interference rather than pure constructive or pure destructive cancellation.

Medical brain scan image showing computer-enhanced view of brain using radiopharmaceutical tracer. Different regions show varying tracer concentrations. Demonstrates nuclear medicine imaging for diagnosis and disease monitoring.

This is a three part diagram of observations from a tape-charging experiment used to test basic principles of electric charge. In part (a), a strip of tape that has been electrically charged is shown interacting with another charged tape. The tapes move apart, indicating repulsion between them. This occurs because both tapes carry the same type of electric charge. In part (b), a tape is shown being handled and repositioned after charge redistribution. The interaction between tapes changes as charge is transferred or rearranged during the process. In part (c), two pieces of tape are brought close together and are observed to move toward each other, indicating attraction. This occurs because the two tapes now carry opposite types of electric charge. The figure reinforces the principle that like charges repel each other, while unlike charges attract each other.

Wheel-and-axle diagram with large radius R and smaller axle radius r. Effort force Fe is applied at the wheel rim, and a rope around the axle lifts a load with force Fr. The diagram shows ideal mechanical advantage increases with R/r.

the geometry and equations for single-slit diffraction minima. Light passes through a single slit of width (D) and travels to a screen a distance (L) away. Rays from the top and bottom edges of the slit travel to a point on the screen at an angle (theta) relative to the central axis. At certain angles, these rays interfere destructively, producing dark regions, or minima, in the diffraction pattern. The vertical distance from the center of the diffraction pattern to a minimum on the screen is labeled (y). The condition for destructive interference is given by the distance between the slits, multiplied by the sine of the observation angle, is equal to a whole-number multiple of the wavelength of the light (D sin theta = m lambda), where (lambda) is the wavelength of the light and (m) is a nonzero integer indicating the order of the minimum. For small angles, this condition can also be written as (D y / L = m lambda), the slit separation multiplied by the vertical distance to the bright or dark fringe, divided by the distance to the screen, equals an integer multiple of the wavelength. The diagram visually connects the geometric path difference to the mathematical expressions used to calculate the positions of dark fringes in a single-slit diffraction pattern.

Two opposite poles of two different magnets are placed near each other. The magnetic flux density B, marked in green, comes out of the north pole and enters the south pole. A conductor is placed between the opposite magnetic poles and carries a current I, marked in red. The magnetic force F‚Çò acts downward, perpendicular to the magnetic flux density. The direction of this force follows the right-hand rule: the thumb points in the direction of the current, the fingers point in the direction of the magnetic field, and the palm shows the direction of the magnetic force.

Nucleons (protons in one color, neutrons in another) tightly packed in nucleus. Nuclear forces hold nucleons together against electrostatic repulsion. Nucleons resist separation and compression. Nucleus volume equals sum of nucleon volumes, shown by different colored spheres.

a compound microscope consisting of two lenses: an objective lens and an eyepiece. A small object of height (ho) is placed just beyond the focal point (Fo) of the objective lens at a distance (do). Rays from the object pass through the objective lens and form a real, inverted, and magnified first image of height (hi) at a distance (di). This first image lies near the focal point (Fe) of the eyepiece and serves as the object for the eyepiece lens. The eyepiece acts as a magnifying glass and produces a final virtual image of height (hi prime), which is magnified even further and viewed by the eye. The dashed backward extensions of the rays indicate the apparent position of the final image on the same side of the eyepiece as the object. Distances between lenses and images, including (do), (di), and (di prime), are labeled along the optical axis. The diagram emphasizes idealized ray behavior, while noting that real lenses introduce aberrations, which are distortions that cause images to deviate from the predictions of thin-lens ray diagrams.

image formation by a flat mirror. Light rays from a bottle reflect off the flat mirror and enter the observer‚Äôs eye, obeying the law of reflection where the angle of incidence equals the angle of reflection. The reflected rays diverge, but when traced backward as dashed lines, they appear to originate from a point behind the mirror, forming a virtual image. The diagram shows that the image distance di behind the mirror is equal to the object distance do in front of the mirror, explaining why flat mirrors produce upright that appear the same size as the object but cannot be projected onto a screen.

polarization of transverse waves using a rope analogy. In panel (a), the rope oscillates in a vertical plane, representing vertically polarized waves that can pass through a vertical slit. In panel (b), the rope oscillates in a horizontal plane, representing horizontally polarized waves that are blocked by a vertical slit. The diagram illustrates that polarization describes the direction of oscillation perpendicular to the direction of wave travel, and that filters or slits only transmit waves polarized in the same direction, a principle that also applies to light waves.
